		<header>
			
			<h1>Debate on the use of national export bans in East Africa</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 October 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, in July 2011 Tanzanian farmers urged the government to lift the ban on cereals exports to enable farmers to earn more. Farmers complained that since the introduction of the ban, the price of a bag of maize received by farmers had fallen by a third, from 45,000 to 30,000 Tanzania shillings. The measure had earlier led to complaints from Tanzanian maize trade association members that the ban was seriously affecting the financial situation of members, as a number of them had taken out loans to finance the trade which was now blocked by the government ban.</p><p>The ban on cereals exports in Kenya has led to complaints from traders there that the measure is ‘against the spirit of East African Community free market protocol’. Press reports indicate that the export ban has affected ‘more than 100,000 tonnes of maize which were set to be transported to Burundi, Rwanda, Uganda and Kenya’.</p><p>The EAC Secretariat meanwhile has pleaded with member state governments ‘to remove barriers that hinder movement of food across the borders’, so that available supplies can be delivered to famine affected areas. An appeal was made for the government of Tanzania to ‘cooperate with fellow member states to alleviate suffering in the region’, while recognising the sovereign right of the Tanzanian government to use ‘its own mechanisms of addressing the food crisis’. The need to change the use of these trade tools within a harmonised regional legal framework was highlighted.</p><p>Within a week of the farmers’ appeal, the government of Tanzania announced that it would consider rescinding the export ban, once 200,000 tonnes of locally produced maize had been bought into the national food reserve. This position was reaffirmed at an EAC Ministerial meeting in mid August, with Tanzanian government representatives rejecting suggestions that the export ban ‘was going against the spirit of East African cooperation’. However the Tanzanian representative affirmed that ‘the ban would be waived once the on-going assessment has established there were enough cereal stocks for local consumption.’ This refers to EAC Secretariat plans to develop a regional food balance sheet to reassure governments on regional food availability and thereby facilitate the movement of foodstuffs from food-surplus to food-deficit areas. Kenyan representatives expressed optimism that within the coming month the Tanzanian authorities would waive export restrictions in response to the worsening food availability situation in Kenya.</p><p>Despite the 6-month export ban introduced in June 2011, food prices have remained high in Tanzania. This is in part attributable to infrastructure constraints in the country which make it ‘difficult to transport agricultural produce from the “grain-basket” Southern-highland region to high demand areas like Dar es Salaam and other urban centers’.</p><p>Press reports note that EAC officials have pointed out that ‘Uganda, Burundi and Rwanda have maintained unrestricted flows of food commodities’ to assist Kenya in meeting the needs of 4 million people affected by famine. These governments have been critical of the Tanzanian export ban.</p><p>In Kenya, meanwhile, efforts are continuing to build up the national food reserve, with the government allocating funds to increase the grain reserve from 2.5 to 8 million bags. The Kenyan government has also introduced a year-long abatement of tariffs on imported corn, wheat and rice from 4 July 2011. However imports will remain subject to port surcharges (equal to around 16% of the cif price, while imported wheat flour is subject to a 16% value-added tax).</p><p>According to analysis by the US Department of Agriculture, in the wheat sector ‘Kenya will be increasingly dependent on imports for the next few years to meet growing local demand’, with imports mainly coming from the Black Sea region, Canada and the USA (the EU supplies only 6.9% of Kenyan imports of wheat).</p><p>Despite the current situation in the cereals sector, according to EAC Permanent Secretary David Nalo, intra-EAC trade had increased from 162 billion Tanzanian shillings in 2005 to TSh342 billion in 2010, with intra-EAC trade projected to reach TSh360 billion in 2011. The Kenya Revenue Authority customs commissioner, Wambui Nama, said that since 2006 ‘Tanzanian exports have doubled while those of Kenya had grown from [Kenyan shillings] Sh53 billion in 2006 to Sh101 billion 2007.’ Ugandan exports have also grown from ‘[U]Sh27 billion to Sh52 billion over the same period’. Wambui Nama maintained that ‘the coming of EAC has increased trade volumes, improved economic performance, enhanced accessibility to investment resources and upped employment creation’. This was seen as a promising start, with more benefits expected to emerge when non-tariff barriers to trade are removed. An audit of the non-tariff barriers in place within the EAC is now under way.</p><p>A range of non-tariff barriers to trade is currently being addressed. This includes efforts to harmonise food standards (e.g. food fortification standards), in order to boost intra-regional trade in commodities such as maize, wheat flour, edible oil, sugar and salt. According to David Nalo, approximately 50% of standards have already been harmonised.</p>
		
		
