				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Despite progress in expanding intra-regional trade following the creation of the EAC customs union, trade in basic foodstuffs remains problematic. This arises from both basic issues, such as the infrastructure constraints on the storage, processing and transportation of cereals and differing national food standards, as well as government policy measures taken in response to food security concerns.</p><p>A coordinated regional policy framework is clearly needed to address underlying food security concerns as a foundation for facilitating intra-regional trade in cereals and cereal products. So long as food security is pursued purely in a national framework, the development of intra-regional trade networks to sustain increased investment in basic food production will be held back. This is an important consideration given the East African region’s vulnerability to periodic droughts and the likely effects of climate change on rainfall and production patterns across the region.</p><p>While the focus of attention in recent months has been on the impact of export bans on the physical availability of foodstuffs in drought affected areas, the economic impact of the Tanzanian export ban on farmers’ incomes and the commercial position of grain traders could potentially carry longer-term implications both for local production of cereals and the construction of intra-regional trade networks in basic cereals.</p><p>Getting to grips with establishing a common regional framework for the promotion of food security and investment in expanded agricultural production, in ways that respect the sovereign rights of member states, would appear to be an important priority for the EAC in the coming months.</p>
		</div>
		
